The paper deals with graph representations and combinatorial optimization, which are typical topics in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The main object of study is rectangle intersection graphs, which are a subclass of geometric intersection graphs, and the paper provides bounds and characterizations for their stab number and exact stab number, which are related to geometric algorithms and computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also uses techniques from graph theory, such as pathwidth and clique number, to derive lower bounds on the stab number, and from forbidden structures and recognition algorithms to characterize certain classes of graphs (cs.DS, cs.CC). Finally, the paper discusses the relationship between stab number and other graph parameters, such as boxicity and splitness, which are topics of interest in graph theory and combinatorial optimization (cs.GT).
